https://leetcode.com/problems/evaluate-reverse-polish-notation/description/

QUESTION:
Input: tokens = ["2","1","+","3","*"]
Output: 9
Explanation: ((2 + 1) * 3) = 9

SOLUTION:
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
TIME COMPLEXITY:O(n)
SPACE COMPLEXITY:O(n)
class Solution {
    public int evalRPN(String[] tokens) {
        Stack<Integer> stack = new Stack<>();

        for (String c : tokens) {
            if (c.equals("+")) {
                stack.push(stack.pop() + stack.pop());
            } else if (c.equals("-")) {
                int second = stack.pop();
                int first = stack.pop();
                stack.push(first - second);
            } else if (c.equals("*")) {
                stack.push(stack.pop() * stack.pop());
            } else if (c.equals("/")) {
                int second = stack.pop();
                int first = stack.pop();
                stack.push(first / second);
            } else {
                stack.push(Integer.parseInt(c));
            }
        }

        return stack.peek();        
    }
}
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Optimal solution:
TIME COMPLEXITY:O(n)
SPACE COMPLEXITY:O(n)
why better?
Same theoretical complexity, but faster in practice because ArrayDeque is not synchronized.
“Stack is a legacy class in Java. I would use Deque<Integer> with ArrayDeque for better performance.”

import java.util.*;

class Solution {
    public int evalRPN(String[] tokens) {
        Deque<Integer> stack = new ArrayDeque<>();

        for (String c : tokens) {
            switch (c) {
                case "+":
                    stack.push(stack.pop() + stack.pop());
                    break;

                case "-":
                    int b = stack.pop();
                    int a = stack.pop();
                    stack.push(a - b);
                    break;

                case "*":
                    stack.push(stack.pop() * stack.pop());
                    break;

                case "/":
                    int divisor = stack.pop();
                    int dividend = stack.pop();
                    stack.push(dividend / divisor);
                    break;

                default:
                    stack.push(Integer.parseInt(c));
            }
        }

        return stack.peek();
    }
}


